05572nam a22006135i 9780824867331DE-B159720220830111616.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220830t20182017hiu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808248673317 a10.1515/97808248673312doi  a(DE-B1597)484495  a(OCoLC)1076450414  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ahiucUS-HI 4aBL 7aREL0180002bisacsh1 aLee, Ming-huei, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aConfucianism :bIts Roots and Global Significance /cMing-huei Lee; ed. by David Jones, Roger T. Ames, Peter D. Hershock. 1aHonolulu : bUniversity of Hawaii Press, c[2018] 4cÂ©2017  a1 online resource (192 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aConfucian Cultures00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tSeries Editors' Preface -- tEditor's Foreword -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction: Destinies and Prospects of the Confucian Traditions in Modern East Asia -- tPART I: Classical Confucianism and Its Modern Reinterpretations -- t1. Mou Zongsan's Interpretation of Confucianism: Some Hermeneutical Reflections -- t2. Modern New Confucians on the Religiousness of Confucianism -- tPART II: Neo-Confucianism in China and Korea -- t3. The Debate on Ren between Zhu Xi and Huxiang Scholars -- t4. The Four-Seven Debate between Yi Toegye and Gi Gobong and Its Philosophical Purport -- tPART III: Ethics and Politics -- t5. Wang Yangming's Philosophy and Modern Theories of Democracy: A Reconstructive Interpretation -- t6. Confucianism, Kant, and Virtue Ethics -- t7. A Critique of Jiang Qing's "Political Confucianism" -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 aOpen Accessuhttps://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_abf2funrestricted online access2star  a"In Confucianism: Its Roots and Global Significance, English language readers get a rare opportunity to read the work in a single volume of one of Taiwan's most distinguished scholars. Although Lee Ming-huei has published in English before, the corpus of his non-Chinese writings is in German. Readers of this volume will discover the hard-mindedness and precision of thinking associated with German philosophy as they enter into Lee's discussions of Confucianism. Progressing through the book, they will be constantly reminded that all philosophy should be truly comparative. . . . "The work is divided into three parts: Classical Confucianism and Its Modern Re-Interpretations, Neo-Confucianism in China and Korea, and Ethics and Politics. These sections reveal the full range of Lee Ming-huei's thinking, including his view of Confucian philosophy's reach to encompass the whole of East Asia, Korea in particular. In the Ethics and Politics section, readers get a taste of Lee's return to his own tradition through the lens of Kantian philosophy with his analysis of Confucius and Virtue Ethics. His thinking through Mou Zongsan's interpretation of Confucianism, Zhu Xi, and the Huxiang scholars' debate on ren and the unfolding of discussions over the 'four buddings' and 'seven feelings' in Korea by Yi Toegye and Gi Gobong set up the subsequent chapters of the book: a reconstruction of Wang Yangming's philosophy and theories of democracy and a critique of Jiang Qing's 'Political Confucianism.' To be sure, the interrelated ideas and arguments presented here contribute significantly to the Confucian project in English-speaking countries across the world." -from the Editor's Foreword  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0 uhttps://www.degruyter.com/dg/page/open-access-policy  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2022) 7aRELIGION / Confucianism.2bisacsh1 aAmes, Roger T., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aHershock, Peter D., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt